    <div><h2>CREATIVITY AS RRESISTANCE</h2>
        <p>The murals are bold, messy, political, and unapologetically raw, just like Berlin itself. From iconic images like The Fraternal Kiss to abstract protests against oppression, the East Side Gallery embodies how creativity can resist silence. For young creatives, this place is a reminder that art doesn't always belong in white cubes or curated museums, it can happen on cracked cement, under the sky, where everyone has access.</p></div>
        <div><h2>INSPIRATION THAT NEVER AGES</h2>
        <p>More than 30 years later, the East Side Gallery is still alive. Some murals have been restored, others left to fade, but all of them invite new interpretations. For creatives, this mix of permanence and decay is a lesson: nothing has to be perfect or permanent to inspire. It's a reminder that the best ideas often come from imperfection, experimentation, and daring to leave a mark, even if it won't last forever.</p>


<p>Visiting tip: Go early in the morning or late in the evening when the crowds thin out. That's when the wall feels less like a tourist spot and more like a quiet dialogue between you, the city, and decades of stories painted in color.</p></div>
